05185nam a22008295i 9780231544504DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20172017nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016057704  a(OCoLC)984688290  a97802315445047 a10.7312/khvo183022doi  a(DE-B1597)480270  a(OCoLC)967457569  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPG3447.V47bG6713 2017 4aPG3447.V47bG6713 2017 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a891.73/32231 aKhvoshchinskaya, Sofia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCity Folk and Country Folk /cSofia Khvoshchinskaya. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRussian Library00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tNotes on the Translation -- tPart I. City Folk and Country Folk -- t1 -- t2 -- t3 -- t4 -- t5 -- t6 -- t7 -- t8 -- t9 -- t10 -- tPART II. City Folk and Country Folk -- t11 -- t12 -- t13 -- t14 -- t15 -- t16 -- t17 -- t18 -- t190 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn unsung gem of nineteenth-century Russian literature, City Folk and Country Folk is a seemingly gentle yet devastating satire of Russia's aristocratic and pseudo-intellectual elites in the 1860s. Translated into English for the first time, the novel weaves an engaging tale of manipulation, infatuation, and female assertiveness that takes place one year after the liberation of the empire's serfs.Upending Russian literary clichés of female passivity and rural gentry benightedness, Sofia Khvoshchinskaya centers her story on a common-sense, hardworking noblewoman and her self-assured daughter living on their small rural estate. The antithesis of the thoughtful, intellectual, and self-denying young heroines created by Khvoshchinskaya's male peers, especially Ivan Turgenev, seventeen-year-old Olenka ultimately helps her mother overcome a sense of duty to her "betters" and leads the two to triumph over the urbanites' financial, amorous, and matrimonial machinations.Sofia Khvoshchinskaya and her writer sisters closely mirror Britain's Brontës, yet Khvoshchinskaya's work contains more of Jane Austen's wit and social repartee, as well as an intellectual engagement reminiscent of Elizabeth Gaskell's condition-of-England novels. Written by a woman under a male pseudonym, this brilliant and entertaining exploration of gender dynamics on a post-emancipation Russian estate offers a fresh and necessary point of comparison with the better-known classics of nineteenth-century world literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCountry lifezRussiaxHistoryy19th centuryvFiction. 0aGentryzRussiavFiction. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aFavorov, Nora.1 aHoogenboom, Hilde, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311054330808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2017z9783110540550oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017z978311062526408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2017z9783110548198oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUrban Studies and Social Rights eBook Package PP 2016-2019z978311063851640uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/khvo1830240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231544504423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231544504/original  a978-3-11-054330-8  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-062526-4  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE